title: For Sale:  Factory manuals for Sperry Ball Turret 50 cal. & B17 plus medals / tags from tail gunner
postcontent: This is a very interesting lot from the family of a WW2 B17 Flying Fortress crewman.  The lot included all manuals & records for a B17f with the serial number 42-30301.  Many are marked restricted, as this was when the B17 was a new type of weapon.  There is a section on pilot training & what effect the aircraft has on the body...how to care for injured crew while still firing the guns etc..  the is an operational manual from Sperry Turret 50 cal aerial machine guns.  There is a wealth of factory training material from Boeing Seattle on the B17.  This all belonged to a crewman (Robert M. Baldi).  One of the crew who accepted delivery of the brand new plane, trained on it, then flew it into combat over Germany.  The plane was named "Idots Delight" in the nose art, and it was shot to pieces over Germany, but limped almost home to England...ditched in the English Channel.  Also included are 8 medals won by the serviceman.  Interesting ones with diving eagle w/lightning in both claws, aerial machine gunner awards & many more.  It is a fascinating lot.  I can send more photos upon request.  Thank you.

title: For Sale:  Kel Tec RFB, 18", 7.62 NATO
postcontent: Kel Tec RFB 18" 7.62 NATO   RFB stands for Rifle, Forward-ejecting Bullpup. Why forward-ejecting? Because it allows the RFB to be the first truly ambidextrous 7.62 NATO Bullpup ever developed. The patented, dual-extractor system maintains control of the case from the moment it leaves the magazine and upon firing, pulls the fired case from the chamber and lifts them to push them into an ejection chute above the barrel, where they exit. The Bullpup configuration and tilting-block mechanism allow the 18" model to be only 26.1" long, or as much as 14" shorter in overall length than its competitors with equal barrel lengths. Furthermore, the stock and mechanism cross-section is similar to a conventional rifle, in stark contrast to existing Bullpup rifles. The RFB is also the safest Bullpup ever developed because the breech is separated from the shooters face by two layers of 1.6 mm steel. In the highly unlikely event of a case rupture, gas expansion is directed downwards through the magazine well to protect the shooters head and face. The RFB is a short-stroke gas piston operated semi-automatic rifle in 7.62 mm NATO caliber. It accepts standard metric FAL type magazines which work "drop free" and do not need to be tilted in. One 20 round magazine is included*. Barrels on current models are 18" long, with a chrome lined bore and chamber. The muzzle is threaded 5/8x24 TPI and comes equipped with our A2-style Flash Hider*.  All controls are fully ambidextrous; the reciprocating operating handle can be switched to either side. The trigger mechanism is second to no other Bullpup ever built and better than nearly all commercial semi-auto rifles. The safety disconnects the trigger and blocks the hammer action. A Mil-Spec Picatinny rail is attached rigidly to the barrel. No open sights are provided, allowing the user to select from the very best new optics and sight systems available. The RFB comes with a two point sling that can be easily configured to suit the user's preference. Available accessories include a free-floating, four-sided Picatinny forend, bipod mounts, a removable bayonet lug for use with NATO style bayonets including our own Folding Bayonet, and many more. Ships FREE!  All FFL Rules and regs apply.  Not interested in trades.Buy this rifle online at www.copsgunshop.net.   https://youtu.be/PbRZ1JvfjvI

title: For Sale:  Ruger Vaquero Birdshead Case Hardened Blued
postcontent: Up for sale is an ultra rare Ruger single action...more on the rare part in a minute. This is a large frame (original Vaquero), not the current "New Vaquero" model. The large frame originals are capable of "Ruger only" loads. It's the blued model with Ruger's faux case hardened frame. The revolver exhibits a slight turn line on the cylinder from handling but has not been fired outside of the Ruger factory. The model number is 00511 and the catalog number is BNVBH-453. Now the backstory on the rare part....Ruger transitioned from the original Vaquero to the new Vaquero late 2004 early 2005 timeframe and stopped making the originals. Thus gun was made in April of 2010 (based on the spent shell casing that came with it from the factory), 5 years after the end of production and 5 years after Ruger stopped the faux case hardening on their blued single actions. Furthermore, the notorious Ruger warning label on the barrel was much smaller and on the underside of the barrel. Prior examples were larger and on the side of the barrel. After acquiring, I called Ruger to verify the manufacter date. Between that and the model/catalog number (which were unique to this particular gun), I was able to find out through a few searches this was one of Ruger's parts clean up releases that were only sold through Davidson's, and that there were likely less than 200 or so made. The late production alone makes it a Ruger collector's object of desire, but the barrel warning label variation puts it over the top. If interested, feel free to reply with your number. I'd be happy to text additional pictures, including the factory label showing model/catalog as well as the dated spent casing. Price is $500

title: For Sale/Trade:  Italian Vetterli m70/87/15
postcontent: For sale or trade is an Italian vetterli m70/87/15. These rifles were originally adopted in 1870 as single shot rifles, then updated to a magazine fed rifle in 1887, then they were then thrown in storage after the carcano was adopted. When WWI rolled around the Italians found themselves short on rifles and converted many of these rifles to 6.5 carcano. This rifle is dated 1885, so it saw all three of these stages. This particular rifle is in good condition, and the bore is still shiny. It also retains the cleaning rod, which is uncommon for these rifles. Has a few cracks in the stock, and there is some sort of repair looking thing on the endge of the bolt face(pictured).These are considered to be unsafe to fire, since they were meant for black powder cartridges. So this rifle is more of a wall hanger, unless you want to hand load your own reduced load ammo.
